but that limit is approached gradually, starting from a positive value, and consequently the consumption function is not the degenerate cÌ€(m) = 0. (Figure 1
presents an example for Ï = 2, R = 0.98, Î² = 1.00, Î“ = 0.99; note that the
horizontal axis is bank balances b = m âˆ’ 1; the part of the consumption function
below the depicted points is uninteresting â€“ c = m â€“ so not worth plotting).
We can summarize as follows. Given that the PF-GIC holds, the interesting
question is whether the FHWC holds. If so, the RIC automatically holds, and
the solution limits into the solution to the unconstrained problem as m â†‘ âˆ.
But even if the FHWC fails, the problem has a well-defined and nondegenerate
solution, whether or not the RIC holds.
Although these results were derived for the perfect foresight case, we know from
work elsewhere in this paper and in other places that the perfect foresight case is
an upper bound for the case with uncertainty. If the upper bound of the MPC
in the perfect foresight case is zero, it is not possible for the upper bound in the
model with uncertainty to be greater than zero, because for any Îº > 0 the level
of consumption in the model with uncertainty would eventually exceed the level
of consumption in the absence of uncertainty.
Ma and Toda (2020) characterize the limits of MPC in a more general framework
that allows for non-CRRA utility as well as capital and labor income risks in a
Markovian setting, and find that in that much more general framework the limiting
MPC is also zero.

